{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413721"},"attributes":{"position":25,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:25:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:25:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12231"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513782"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:14:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:14:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12231"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12231"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.55,0.07,0.22,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98813"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4753"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81204"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1788"},{"type":"tags","id":"3487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33824"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98813"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old man is receiving a transfusion of fresh frozen plasma (FFP) in the hospital. He has a history of selective IgA deficiency. He does not take any regular medications. Five minutes into the transfusion, he develops dyspnoea. Vital signs prior to the transfusion were pulse rate 70/min, respiratory rate 18/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, temperature 36.8\u00b0C, and SpO2 99% on room air. Vital signs after the reaction are pulse rate 130/min, respiratory rate 30/min, blood pressure 90/50 mmHg, temperature 36.8\u00b0C, and SpO2 75% on room air. He is intubated and transferred to the intensive care unit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA transfusion reaction investigation is initiated. He received compatible FFP correctly. Blood tests are pending. Chest x-ray is unmarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute haemolytic transfusion reaction","Anaphylactic transfusion reaction","Transfusion-associated circulatory overload","Transfusion-related acute lung injury","Transfusion-transmitted bacterial sepsis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESelective immunoglobulin A (IgA) deficiency is the most common primary immunodeficiency. Patients present with recurrent sinopulmonary infections. It is also associated with autoimmune and gastrointestinal conditions, including coeliac disease. Some patients with severe IgA deficiency may develop anaphylaxis to blood products due to the interaction of anti-IgA antibodies with IgA present in blood products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransfusion reactions are adverse events associated with the transfusion of whole blood or its components. They may be mild or severe, and can be categorised as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmune-mediated, acute (\u0026lt;24 hours after transfusion)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eacute haemolytic transfusion reaction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Emild allergic transfusion reaction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eanaphylactic transfusion reaction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etransfusion-related acute lung injury (TRALI)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efebrile non-haemolytic transfusion reaction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-immune mediated, acute\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etransfusion-associated circulatory overload (TACO)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etransfusion-transmitted bacterial sepsis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmune-mediated, non-acute (\u0026gt;24 hours after transfusion)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Edelayed haemolytic transfusion reaction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etransfusion-associated graft versus host disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAllergic transfusion reactions (ATRs) occur in up to 3% of transfusions, with the highest rates in platelet and plasma products. Mild allergic reactions are typically characterised by pruritus, urticaria, and angioedema. More severe or \u003Cstrong\u003Eanaphylactic reactions\u003C/strong\u003E are accompanied by respiratory distress and wheezing. Hypotension and shock can also occur. Fever is not usually present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETRALI\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute non-cardiogenic pulmonary oedema associated with hypoxemia and hypotension which occurs within 6 hours of transfusion. While this is an important differential to consider, the history of selective IgA deficiency suggests an anaphylactic transfusion reaction. Additionally, the absence of pulmonary infiltrates on chest x-ray makes TRALI less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETACO\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as the occurence of new or worsening respiratory symptoms within 12 hours of transfusion. However, TACO presents with signs of fluid overload such as elevated jugular venous pressure and peripheral oedema, which are not described here. Additionally, the absence of pulmonary infiltrates on chest x-ray makes TACO less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfusion-transmitted bacterial sepsis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents within minutes after starting transfusion with fever, hypotension, chills, and other signs of sepsis. The lack of fever makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute haemolytic transfusion reaction\u003C/strong\u003E may present with the triad of fever, flank pain, and red urine. However, this triad is uncommon. Other clinical features are chills, hypotension, renal failure, back pain, and disseminated intravascular coagulation. This diagnosis is less likely in this case as he received compatible FFP correctly. In addition, the history of selective IgA deficiency suggests an anaphylactic transfusion reaction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Selective IgA deficiency is the most common primary immunodeficiency","Patients with selective IgA deficiency may present with recurrent sinopulmonary infections","Patients with severe selective IgA deficiency with anti-IgA antibodies may develop anaphylaxis to IgA present in blood products","Allergic transfusion reactions (ATRs) are type 1 hypersensitivity reactions, ranging from mild (urticarial) to severe (anaphylactic)"],"references":["Adkins BD, Lawicki S, Johnson M, Eichbaum Q. Mild Allergic Transfusion Reactions: Impact of Associated Clinical Symptoms? Am J Clin Pathol. 2019;151(3):344-8.","Abdallah R, Rai H, Panch SR. Transfusion Reactions and Adverse Events. Clin Lab Med. 2021;41(4):669-96.","Lifeblood. Classification and incidence of adverse events [Internet]. [cited 2024 Jul 02]. Available from: https://www.lifeblood.com.au/health-professionals/clinical-practice/adverse-events/classification-incidence","Yel L. Selective IgA Deficiency. J Clin Immunol. 2010;30(1):10-6."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81204"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12231"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81204"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-17T17:55:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-17T17:56:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4753"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98813"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data"